WEBVTT

00:20.660 --> 00:24.340
XV. Winter Animals.

00:25.980 --> 00:31.560
When the ponds were firmly frozen they afforded not only new and shorter routes to many points,

00:32.100 --> 00:38.800
but new views from their surfaces of the familiar landscape around them. When I crossed Flint's

00:38.800 --> 00:44.360
Pond after it was covered with snow, though I had often paddled about and skated over it,

00:45.100 --> 00:53.340
it was so unexpectedly wide and so strange that I could think of nothing but Baffin's Bay. The

00:53.340 --> 00:59.160
Lincoln Hills rose up around me at the extremity of a snowy plain, in which I did not remember

00:59.160 --> 01:06.720
to have stood before, and the fishermen, at an indeterminable distance over the ice, moving

01:06.720 --> 01:14.760
slowly about with their wolfish dogs, passed for sealers or Eskimo, or in misty weather

01:14.760 --> 01:21.200
loomed like fabulous creatures, and I did not know whether they were giants or pygmies.

01:22.060 --> 01:28.660
I took this course when I went to lecture in Lincoln in the evening, travelling in no road

01:28.660 --> 01:35.820
and passing no house between my own hut and the lecture-room. In Goose Pond, which lay in my way,

01:36.180 --> 01:42.460
a colony of muskrats dwelt and raised their cabins high above the ice, though none could be seen

01:42.460 --> 01:49.900
abroad when I crossed it. Walden, being like the rest usually bare of snow, or with only shallow

01:49.900 --> 01:55.560
and interrupted drifts on it, was my yard where I could walk freely when the snow was nearly two

01:55.560 --> 02:03.720
feet deep on a level elsewhere and the villagers were confined to their streets. There, far from

02:03.720 --> 02:08.560
the village street, and except at very long intervals from the jingle of sleigh bells,

02:09.200 --> 02:17.740
I slid and skated, as in a vast moose-yard well trodden, overhung by oak woods and solemn pines

02:17.740 --> 02:26.940
bent down with snow or bristling with icicles. For sounds in winter nights, and often in winter days,

02:27.420 --> 02:35.320
I heard the forlorn but melodious note of a hooting owl indefinitely far, such a sound as

02:35.320 --> 02:42.440
the frozen earth would yield if struck with a suitable plectrum, the very lingua vernacular

02:42.440 --> 02:49.740
of Walden wood, and quite familiar to me at last, though I never saw the bird while it was making it.

02:51.160 --> 02:55.300
I seldom opened my door in a winter evening without hearing it.

02:56.180 --> 03:01.380
Hoo, hoo, hoo, hooter, hoo,

03:02.860 --> 03:10.060
sounded sonorously, and the first three syllables accented somewhat like how dare do,

03:11.120 --> 03:20.940
or sometimes hoo, hoo, only. One night, in the beginning of winter, before the pond froze over,

03:20.940 --> 03:27.320
about nine o'clock, I was startled by the loud honking of a goose, and stepped to the door,

03:28.260 --> 03:33.500
heard the sound of their wings like a tempest in the woods as they flew low over my house.

03:34.400 --> 03:41.120
They passed over the pond toward Fairhaven, seemingly deterred from settling by my light,

03:42.080 --> 03:45.440
their Commodore honking all the while with a regular beat.

03:46.620 --> 03:54.840
Suddenly an unmistakable cat-owl, from very near me, with the most harsh and tremendous voice I

03:54.840 --> 04:00.340
ever heard from any inhabitant of the woods, responded at regular intervals to the goose,

04:00.940 --> 04:14.960
as if determined to expose and disgrace this intruder from Hudson's Bay, by exhibiting a

04:14.960 --> 04:15.800
horizon.

04:17.100 --> 04:23.340
What do you mean by alarming the citadel at this time of night consecrated to me?

04:23.840 --> 04:26.840
Do you think I am ever caught napping at such an hour,

04:26.980 --> 04:32.280
and that I have not got lungs and a larynx as well as yourself?

04:36.260 --> 04:40.300
It was one of the most thrilling discords I ever heard.

04:41.190 --> 04:48.360
And yet, if you had a discriminating ear, there were in it the elements of a Concord such as these

04:48.360 --> 04:57.740
planes never saw nor heard. I also heard the whooping of the ice in the pond, my great bedfellow

04:57.740 --> 05:04.480
in that part of Concord, as if it were restless in its bed and would fain turn over, were troubled

05:04.480 --> 05:12.400
with flatulency, and had dreams, or I was waked by the cracking of the ground by the frost,

05:13.020 --> 05:20.020
as if someone had driven a team against my door, and in the morning would find a crack in the earth

05:20.020 --> 05:27.500
a quarter of a mile long and a third of an inch wide. Sometimes I heard the foxes as they ranged

05:27.500 --> 05:33.760
over the snow crust in moonlight nights, in search of a partridge or other game,

05:34.480 --> 05:41.320
barking raggedly and demoniacly like forest dogs, as if laboring with some anxiety,

05:41.900 --> 05:49.940
or seeking expression, struggling for light, and to be dogs outright and run freely in the streets.

05:51.080 --> 05:57.340
For if we take the ages into our account, may there not be a civilization going on among brutes,

05:57.340 --> 06:03.860
as well as men? They seemed to me to be rudimental burrowing men,

06:05.280 --> 06:08.940
still standing on their defense, awaiting their transformation.

06:11.260 --> 06:18.200
Sometimes one came near to my window, attracted by my light, barked a vulpine curse at me,

06:18.200 --> 06:22.760
and then retreated, usually the red squirrel.

06:26.120 --> 06:32.120
Sirius Hudsonius waked me in the dawn, coursing over the roof and up and down the sides of the

06:32.120 --> 06:39.200
house, as if sent out of the woods for this purpose. In the course of the winter I threw out

06:39.200 --> 06:45.060
half a bushel of ears of sweet corn which had not got ripe, on to the snow crust by my door,

06:45.060 --> 06:49.940
and was amused by watching the motions of the various animals which were baited by it.

06:50.960 --> 06:58.320
In the twilight and the night the rabbits came regularly and made a hearty meal. All day long

06:58.320 --> 07:03.020
the red squirrels came and went, and afforded me much entertainment by their maneuvers.

07:04.040 --> 07:09.680
One would approach, at first warily, through the shrub oaks, running over the snow crust by

07:09.680 --> 07:16.960
and starts like a leaf blown by the wind, now a few paces this way, with wonderful speed and

07:16.960 --> 07:23.900
waste of energy, making inconceivable haste with his trotters, as if it were for a wager,

07:25.360 --> 07:31.150
and now as many paces that way, but never getting on more than half a rod at a time,

07:31.520 --> 07:38.700
and then suddenly pausing with a ludicrous expression and a gratuitous somerset, as if all

07:38.700 --> 07:45.440
the eyes in the universe were eyed on him. For all the motions of a squirrel, even in the most

07:45.440 --> 07:54.360
solitary recesses of the forest, imply spectators as much as those of a dancing girl, wasting more

07:54.360 --> 07:59.260
time and delay and circumspection than would have sufficed to walk the whole distance.

07:59.880 --> 08:05.460
I never saw one walk, and then suddenly, before you could say Jack Robinson,

08:05.460 --> 08:11.960
he would be in the top of a young pitch pine winding up his clock and chiding all imaginary

08:11.960 --> 08:20.120
spectators, soliloquizing and talking to all the universe at the same time, for no reason that I

08:20.120 --> 08:27.460
could ever detect, or he himself was aware of, I suspect. At length he would reach the corn,

08:28.020 --> 08:33.460
and selecting a suitable ear, frisk about in the same uncertain trigonometrical way,

08:33.460 --> 08:39.700
to the tuckmost stick of my wood-pile before my window, where he looked me in the face,

08:40.080 --> 08:46.200
and there sit for hours. Supplying himself with a new ear from time to time,

08:46.580 --> 08:53.100
nibbling at first voraciously and throwing the half-naked cobs about, till at length he grew

08:53.100 --> 09:00.500
more dainty still and played with his food, tasting only the inside of the kernel and the ear,

09:00.500 --> 09:07.120
which was held balanced over the stick by one paw, slipping from his careless grasp,

09:07.640 --> 09:13.180
and fell to the ground, when he would look over at it with a ludicrous expression of uncertainty,

09:14.280 --> 09:21.040
as if suspecting that it had life, with a mind not made up whether to get it again, or a new one,

09:21.480 --> 09:28.120
or be off, now thinking of corn, then listening to hear what was in the wind.

09:29.340 --> 09:36.020
So the little impudent fellow would waste many an ear in a forenoon, till at last,

09:36.480 --> 09:43.560
seizing some longer and plumper one, considerably bigger than himself, and skillfully balancing it,

09:43.780 --> 09:50.540
he would set out with it to the woods, like a tiger with a buffalo, by the same zigzag

09:50.540 --> 09:56.460
course and frequent pauses, scratching along with it as if it were too heavy for him, and

09:56.460 --> 10:02.200
all the while making its fall a diagonal between a perpendicular and horizontal,

10:02.960 --> 10:11.320
being determined to put it through at any rate. A singularly frivolous and whimsical fellow,

10:12.220 --> 10:17.320
and so he would get off with it to where he lived, perhaps carry it to the top of a pine

10:17.320 --> 10:23.320
tree forty or fifty rods distant, and I would afterwards find the cobs strewn about the woods

10:23.320 --> 10:32.460
in various directions. At length the jays arrive, whose discordant screams were heard long before,

10:32.860 --> 10:38.660
as they were warily making their approach an eighth of a mile off, and in a stealthy and

10:38.660 --> 10:45.940
sneaking manner they flit from tree to tree, nearer and nearer, and pick up the kernels which the

10:45.940 --> 10:54.380
dropped. Then, sitting on a pitch pine bough, they attempt to swallow in their haste a kernel

10:54.380 --> 11:00.340
which is too big for their throats and chokes them, and after great labor they disgorge it,

11:01.220 --> 11:05.200
and spend an hour in the endeavor to crack it by repeated blows with their bills.

11:06.320 --> 11:13.740
They were manifestly thieves, and I had not much respect for them, but the squirrels,

11:13.740 --> 11:19.000
though at first shy, went to work as if they were taking what was their own.

11:20.820 --> 11:27.160
Meanwhile also came the chickadees in flocks, which, picking up the crumbs the squirrels had

11:27.160 --> 11:33.260
dropped, flew to the nearest twig, and placing them under their claws, hammered away at them

11:33.260 --> 11:39.640
with their little bills, as if it were an insect in the bark, till they were sufficiently reduced

11:39.640 --> 11:47.660
for their slender throats. A little flock of these tit-mice came daily to pick a dinner out

11:47.660 --> 11:54.780
of my wood-pile, or the crumbs at my door, with faint flitting, lisping notes, like the tinkling

11:54.780 --> 12:03.660
of icicles in the grass, or else with sprightly, day, day, day, or more rarely in spring-like days,

12:03.660 --> 12:12.980
a wiry, summery Phoebe from the wood-side. They were so familiar that, at length,

12:13.320 --> 12:19.140
one alighted on an armful of wood which I was carrying in and pecked at the sticks without fear.

12:20.360 --> 12:26.360
I once had a sparrow alight upon my shoulder for a moment while I was hoeing in a village garden,

12:27.000 --> 12:33.300
and I felt that I was more distinguished by that circumstance than I should have been

12:33.760 --> 12:41.080
by any epaulette I could have worn. The squirrels also grew at last to be quite familiar,

12:41.660 --> 12:48.300
and occasionally stepped upon my shoe, when that was the nearest way. When the ground was

12:48.300 --> 12:54.680
not yet quite covered, and again, near the end of winter, when the snow was melted on my south

12:54.680 --> 13:01.360
hill-side and about my wood-pile, the partridges came out of the woods morning and evening to feed

13:01.360 --> 13:09.480
there. Whichever side you walk in the woods the partridge bursts away on whirring wings,

13:09.840 --> 13:16.620
jarring the snow from the dry leaves and twigs on high, which comes sifting down in the sun-beams

13:16.620 --> 13:26.140
like golden dust, for this brave bird is not to be scared by winter. It is frequently covered up

13:26.140 --> 13:34.240
by drifts, and, it is said, sometimes plunges from on wing into the soft snow where it remains

13:34.240 --> 13:42.500
concealed for a day or two. I used to start them in the open land also, where they had come out

13:42.500 --> 13:50.020
of the woods at sunset to bud the wild apple trees. They will come regularly every evening

13:50.020 --> 13:57.260
to particular trees, where the cunning sportsman lies and wait for them, and the distant orchards

13:57.260 --> 14:04.820
next to the woods suffer thus not a little. I am glad that the partridge gets fed at any rate.

14:04.820 --> 14:10.920
It is nature's own bird which lives on buds and diet drink.

14:12.440 --> 14:21.020
In dark winter mornings, or in short winter afternoons, I sometimes heard a pack of hounds

14:21.020 --> 14:28.800
threading all the woods with hounding cry and yelp, unable to resist the instinct of the chase,

14:29.520 --> 14:35.060
and the note of the hunting-horn at intervals, proving that man was in the rear.

14:36.140 --> 14:42.340
The woods ring again, and yet no fox bursts forth on to the open level of the pond,

14:42.880 --> 14:50.460
nor following pack pursuing their actaeon, and perhaps at evening I see the hunters returning

14:50.460 --> 14:56.960
with a single brush trailing from their sleigh for a trophy, seeking their inn.

14:57.700 --> 15:03.240
They tell me that if the fox would remain in the bosom of the frozen earth he would be safe,

15:04.360 --> 15:10.700
or if B would run in a straight line away no fox-hound could overtake him,

15:11.420 --> 15:16.920
but having left his pursuers far behind he stops to rest and listen till they come up,

15:17.320 --> 15:21.960
and when he runs he circles round to his old haunts where the hunters await him.

15:23.340 --> 15:29.840
Sometimes, however, he will run upon a wall many rods, and then leap off far to one side,

15:30.300 --> 15:37.260
and he appears to know that water will not retain his scent. A hunter told me that he once saw a

15:37.260 --> 15:43.720
fox pursued by hounds burst out on to Walden when the ice was covered with shallow puddles,

15:44.280 --> 15:47.500
run part way across, and then return to the same shore.

15:48.740 --> 15:56.480
Ere long the hounds arrived, but here they lost the scent. Sometimes a pack hunting by themselves

15:56.480 --> 16:03.420
would pass my door, and circle round my house and yelp and hound without regarding me, as if

16:03.420 --> 16:08.920
afflicted by a species of madness, so that nothing could divert them from the pursuit.

16:09.960 --> 16:16.420
Thus they circle until they fall upon the recent trail of a fox, for a wise hound will

16:16.420 --> 16:23.620
forsake everything else for this. One day a man came to my hut from Lexington to inquire after his

16:23.620 --> 16:30.120
hound, that made a large track, and had been hunting for a week by himself, but I fear that

16:30.120 --> 16:35.140
he was not the wiser for all I told him, for every time I attempted to answer his questions

16:35.140 --> 16:43.560
he interrupted me by asking, What do you do here? He had lost a dog, but found a man.

16:44.260 --> 16:51.180
One old hunter, who has a dry tongue, who used to come to bathe in Walden once every year when the

16:51.180 --> 16:57.720
water was warmest, and at such times looked in upon me, told me that many years ago he took his

16:57.720 --> 17:04.620
gun one afternoon and went out for a cruise in Walden Wood, and as he walked the Wayland road he

17:04.620 --> 17:12.480
heard the cry of hounds approaching, and ere long a fox leaped the wall into the road, and as quick

17:12.480 --> 17:19.280
as thought leaped the other wall out of the road, and his swift bullet had not touched him.

17:20.800 --> 17:27.080
Some way behind came an old hound and her three pups in full pursuit, hunting on their own accord,

17:27.600 --> 17:34.640
and disappeared again in the woods. Late in the afternoon, as he was resting in the thick woods

17:34.640 --> 17:40.720
south of Walden, he heard the voice of the hounds far over toward Fair Haven still pursuing the fox,

17:41.670 --> 17:49.330
and on they came, their hounding cry which made all the woods ring, sounding nearer and nearer,

17:49.940 --> 17:57.120
now from Well Meadow, now from the Baker Farm. For a long time he stood still and listened to

17:57.120 --> 18:05.180
their music, so sweet to a hunter's ear, when suddenly the fox appeared, threading the solemn

18:05.180 --> 18:12.820
aisles with an easy coursing pace, whose sound was concealed by a sympathetic rustle of the leaves,

18:13.580 --> 18:19.840
swift and still, keeping the round, leaving his pursuers far behind,

18:20.220 --> 18:27.360
and leaping upon a rock amid the woods he sat erect and listening, with his back to the hunter.

18:28.340 --> 18:35.160
For a moment compassion restrained the latter's arm, but that was a short-lived mood.

18:35.180 --> 18:40.620
And as quick as thought can follow thought his peace was levelled and whang!

18:41.760 --> 18:49.540
The fox, rolling over the rock, lay dead on the ground. The hunter still kept his place and

18:49.540 --> 18:57.560
listened to the hounds. Still on they came, and now the near woods resounded through all their aisles

18:57.560 --> 19:04.860
with their demoniac cry. At length the old hound burst into view with muzzle to the ground,

19:04.860 --> 19:12.740
and snapping the air as if possessed, and ran directly to the rock. But spying the dead fox

19:13.660 --> 19:21.920
she suddenly ceased her hounding as if struck dumb with amazement, and walked round and round

19:21.920 --> 19:30.180
him in silence. And one by one her pups arrived, and like their mother were sobered into silence

19:30.180 --> 19:36.460
by the mystery. Then the hunter came forward and stood in their midst, and the mystery was solved.

19:37.580 --> 19:43.920
They waited in silence while he skinned the fox, then followed the brush a while, and at length

19:43.920 --> 19:50.480
turned off into the woods again. That evening a Weston squire came to the Concord hunter's

19:50.480 --> 19:56.100
cottage to inquire for his hounds, and told how for a week they had been hunting on their own

19:56.100 --> 20:02.900
from Weston woods. The Concord hunter told him what he knew and offered him the skin,

20:03.540 --> 20:10.520
but the other declined it and departed. He did not find his hounds that night, but the next day

20:10.520 --> 20:14.080
learned that they had crossed the river and put up at a farmhouse for the night.

20:14.760 --> 20:19.000
Whence, having been well fed, they took their departure early in the morning.

20:19.940 --> 20:25.920
The hunter who told me this could remember one Sam Nutting, who used to hunt bears on Fairhaven

20:25.920 --> 20:33.600
ledges, and exchanged their skins for rum in Concord village, who told him even that he had

20:33.600 --> 20:45.120
seen a moose there. Nutting had a famous fox-hound named Burgoyne. He pronounced it Bugene, which my

20:45.120 --> 20:53.720
informant used to borrow. In the vast book of an old trader of this town, who was also a captain,

20:53.720 --> 21:04.360
town clerk, and representative, I find the following entry. January 18, 1742, 43. John Melvin,

21:04.580 --> 21:14.600
credited by one, Gray Fox, zero, two, three. They are not now found here, and in his ledger,

21:14.600 --> 21:28.240
February 7, 1743, Hezekiah Stratton has credit by one half a cat-skin, zero, one, four plus.

21:30.300 --> 21:37.320
Of course a wild cat, for Stratton was a sergeant in the old French war, and would not have got

21:37.320 --> 21:45.620
for hunting less noble game. Credit is given for deer skins also, and they were daily sold.

21:47.020 --> 21:51.500
One man still preserves the horns of the last deer that was killed in this vicinity,

21:51.680 --> 21:56.160
and another has told me the particulars of the hunt in which his uncle was engaged.

21:57.760 --> 22:05.700
The hunters were formerly a numerous and merry crew here. I remember well one Gaunt Nimrod,

22:05.700 --> 22:09.400
who would catch up a leaf by the roadside and play a strain on it,

22:10.140 --> 22:15.520
wilder and more melodious, if my memory serves me, than any hunting-horn.

22:17.300 --> 22:24.980
At midnight, when there was a moon, I sometimes met with hounds in my path prowling about the woods,

22:25.740 --> 22:32.840
which would skulk out of my way, as if afraid, and stand silent amid the bushes till I had passed.

22:34.020 --> 22:40.840
Squirrels and wild mice disputed for my store of nuts. There were scores of pitch pines around

22:40.840 --> 22:47.400
my house, from one to four inches in diameter, which had been gnawed by mice the previous winter,

22:47.920 --> 22:52.760
a Norwegian winter for them, for the snow lay long and deep, and they were obliged to

22:52.760 --> 22:59.800
mix a large proportion of pine bark with their other diet. These trees were alive and apparently

22:59.800 --> 23:06.140
flourishing at midsummer, and many of them had grown afoot, though completely girdled,

23:06.760 --> 23:13.580
but after another winter such were without exception dead. It is remarkable that a single

23:13.580 --> 23:20.420
mouse should thus be allowed a whole pine tree for its dinner, gnawing round instead of up and

23:20.420 --> 23:27.720
down it, but perhaps it is necessary in order to thin these trees, which are wont to grow up densely.

23:28.440 --> 23:36.900
The hares, Lepus Americanus, were very familiar. One had her form under my house all winter,

23:37.540 --> 23:43.680
separated from me only by the flooring, and she startled me each morning by her hasty departure

23:43.680 --> 23:50.480
when I began to stir, thump, thump, thump, striking her head against the floor timbers in her hurry.

23:51.400 --> 23:56.720
They used to come round my door at dusk to nibble the potato pairings which I had thrown out,

23:56.720 --> 24:01.920
and were so nearly the color of the ground that they could hardly be distinguished when still.

24:03.080 --> 24:09.320
Sometimes in the twilight I alternately lost and recovered sight of one sitting motionless under

24:09.320 --> 24:15.260
my window. When I opened my door in the evening off they would go with a squeak and a bounce.

24:16.900 --> 24:24.040
Near at hand they only excited my pity. One evening one sat by my door two paces from me,

24:24.040 --> 24:32.060
at first trembling with fear, yet unwilling to move. A poor wee thing, lean and bony,

24:32.580 --> 24:41.660
with ragged ears and sharp nose, scant tail and slender paws. It looked as if nature no

24:41.660 --> 24:51.220
longer contained the breed of nobler bloods, but stood on her last toes. Its large eyes appeared

24:51.220 --> 25:01.800
young and unhealthy, almost dropsicle. I took a step and low away its scud with an elastic spring

25:01.800 --> 25:06.340
over the snow crust, straightening its body and its limbs into graceful length,

25:06.940 --> 25:12.780
and soon put the forest between me and itself, the wild free venison,

25:13.420 --> 25:17.420
asserting its vigor and the dignity of nature.

25:19.220 --> 25:25.880
Not without reason was its slenderness. Such then was its nature.

25:28.100 --> 25:36.820
Lepis, levipis, light foot, methinks. What is a country without rabbits and partridges?

25:36.820 --> 25:44.960
They are among the most simple and indigenous animal products. Ancient and venerable families,

25:45.400 --> 25:51.820
known to antiquity as to modern times, of the very hue and substance of nature,

25:52.560 --> 26:01.460
nearest allied to leaves and to the ground, and to one another. It is either winged or it is legged.

26:01.460 --> 26:08.160
It is hardly as if you had seen a wild creature when a rabbit or a partridge bursts away,

26:08.860 --> 26:17.260
only a natural one, as much to be expected as rustling leaves. The partridge and the rabbit

26:17.260 --> 26:24.220
are still sure to thrive like true natives of the soil, whatever revolutions occur.

26:24.920 --> 26:31.780
If the forest is cut off, the sprouts and bushes which spring up afford them concealment,

26:32.100 --> 26:40.080
and they become more numerous than ever. That must be a poor country indeed, that does not support

26:40.080 --> 26:47.300
a hare. Our woods team with them both, and around every swamp may be seen the partridge

26:47.300 --> 26:55.760
or rabbit walk, beset with twiggy fences and horse-hair snares, which some cowboy tends.

